          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">Trilateral agreement</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/ministers-next-meeting-japan-agreement.png" alt="The ministers agreed to hold their next ministerial meeting in Japan" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;"><i>The ministers agreed to hold their next ministerial meeting in Japan. Credits: Jung Yeon-je/AFP</i></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Is the East strengthening ties to counter Trump’s tariffs? China, South Korea, and Japan negotiated a <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-31-03-2025-h1-1-trilateral-free-trade-agreement?source=website" target="_blank">trilateral free-trade agreement</a> to create a favorable trade and investment environment. This marks the first high-level trade meeting between the countries in five years. </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;filter:blur(5px);">
          South Korea's Minister of Trade, Ahn Duk-geun, emphasized a joint response to tackle global challenges. Chinese official Wang Liping said the three countries should safeguard the multilateral trading system amid growing unilateralism and protectionism. These three countries account for 20% of the world's population, 24% of the world economy, and 19% of world merchandise trade.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>
